<dl id="n54107h"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54107h">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54107h"> 107(h)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Alakabah / (pledge of steep) <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54107h"><li>FW 310.28f </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/lexma.htm#n54107h">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/ma/l39ma.htm#n54107h">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54107h">MS BL 47479-168</ms> </li><li>JJA 54:257 <a name="mad6" href="../../ff/fdra/mda.htm#mad6">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/ma/mad6.htm#n54107h">Draft: II.3&sect;1.6</a> zzzzzz</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[T]</font>welve men of Yathrib pledged their faith to Islam, solemnly promising to worship none but the One True God, to lead pure and virtuous lives, and obey the Prophet in all that was right. This was <mark>the First Pledge of Al-Akabah, or The Steep</mark>. It was afterwards called the &ldquo;Women&apos;s Pledge,&rdquo; because there was no mention of fighting for the cause, and the profession of faith was the same as that made by women on joining Islam. <small> Edith Holland, <a name="EHSM" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EHSM"><cite title="source">The Story of Mohammed</cite></a> (1914) 73</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
